[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] In mathematics, the **bisection method** is a root-finding method that applies to any continuous function for which one knows two values with opposite signs.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The method consists of repeatedly bisecting the interval defined by these values, then selecting the subinterval in which the function changes sign, which therefore must contain a root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] It is a very simple and robust method, but it is also relatively slow.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Because of this, it is often used to obtain a rough approximation to a solution which is then used as a starting point for more rapidly converging methods.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The method is also called the **interval halving** method, the **binary search method**, or the **dichotomy method**.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] For polynomials, more elaborate methods exist for testing the existence of a root in an interval (Descartes' rule of signs, Sturm's theorem, Budan's theorem).
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] They allow extending the bisection method into efficient algorithms for finding all real roots of a polynomial; see Real-root isolation.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The method is applicable for numerically solving the equation $f(x)=0$ for the real variable x , where f is a continuous function defined on an interval $[a,b]$ and where $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] In this case a and b are said to bracket a root since, by the intermediate value theorem, the continuous function f must have at least one root in the interval $(a,b)$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] At each step the method divides the interval in two parts/halves by computing the midpoint $c=(a+b)/2$ of the interval and the value of the function $f(c)$ at that point.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] If c itself is a root then the process has succeeded and stops.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Otherwise, there are now only two possibilities: either $f(a)$ and $f(c)$ have opposite signs and bracket a root, or $f(c)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs and bracket a root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The method selects the subinterval that is guaranteed to be a bracket as the new interval to be used in the next step.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] In this way an interval that contains a zero of f is reduced in width by 50% at each step.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The process is continued until the interval is sufficiently small.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Explicitly, if $f(c)=0$ then c may be taken as the solution and the process stops.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] In both cases, the new $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs, so the method may be applied to this smaller interval.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Once the process starts, the signs at the left and right ends of the interval remain the same for all iterations.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] In order to determine when the iteration should stop, it is necessary to consider various possible stopping conditions with respect to a tolerance ( $\epsilon$ ).
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] $|f(p_{N})|<\epsilon$ does not give an accurate result to within $\epsilon$ unless $|f'(p_{N})|\geq 1$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The other two possibilities represent different concepts: the absolute difference $|c-a|\leq 5\times 10^{-t}$ says that c and a are the same to t decimal places, while the relative difference $\left|{\frac {c-a}{c}}\right|\leq 5\times 10^{-t}$ says that c and a are the same to t significant figures.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] If nothing is known about the value of the root, then relative tolerance is the best stopping condition.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The input for the method is a continuous function f and an interval $[a,b]$ , such that the function values $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ are of opposite sign (there is at least one zero crossing within the interval).
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Examine the sign of $f(c)$ and replace either a or b with c so that there is a zero crossing within the new interval.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] First, two numbers a and b have to be found such that $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Because the function is continuous, there must be a root within the interval [1, 2].
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] After 13 iterations, it becomes apparent that there is a convergence to about 1.521: a root for the polynomial.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The bisection method has been generalized to multi-dimensional functions.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Such methods are called **generalized bisection methods**.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Some of these methods are based on computing the topological degree.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] The **characteristic bisection method** uses only the signs of a function in different points.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Lef *f* be a function from R*d* to R*d*, for some integer *d* ≥ 2.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] A **characteristic polyhedron** (also called an **admissible polygon**) of *f* is a polyhedron in R*d*, having 2*d* vertices, such that in each vertex **v**, the combination of signs of *f*(**v**) is unique.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] A **proper edge** of a characteristic polygon is a edge between a pair of vertices, such that the sign vector differs by only a single sign.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] In the above example, the proper edges of the characteristic quadrilateral are AB, AC, BD and CD.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] A **diagonal** is a pair of vertices, such that the sign vector differs by all *d* signs.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] In the above example, the diagonals are AD and BC.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] At each iteration, the algorithm picks a proper edge of the polyhedron (say, A—B), and computes the signs of *f* in its mid-point (say, M).
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Suppose the diameter (= length of longest proper edge) of the original characteristic polyhedron is D.
[src:newton-raphson-method/bisection-method] Then, at least $\log _{2}(D/\varepsilon )$ bisections of edges are required so that the diameter of the remaining polygon will be at most $\varepsilon$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] In numerical analysis, **fixed-point iteration** is a method of computing fixed points of a function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] More generally, the function f can be defined on any metric space with values in that same space.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] An *attracting fixed point* of a function *f* is a fixed point *x*fix of *f* with a neighborhood *U* of "close enough" points around *x*fix such that for any value of x in *U*, the fixed-point iteration sequence $x,\ f(x),\ f(f(x)),\ f(f(f(x))),\dots$ is contained in *U* and converges to *x*fix.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] The basin of attraction of *x*fix is the largest such neighborhood *U*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] The natural cosine function ("natural" means in radians, not degrees or other units) has exactly one fixed point, and that fixed point is attracting.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] In this case, "close enough" is not a stringent criterion at all—to demonstrate this, start with *any* real number and repeatedly press the *cos* key on a calculator (checking first that the calculator is in "radians" mode).
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] It eventually converges to the Dottie number (about 0.739085133), which is a fixed point.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] That is where the graph of the cosine function intersects the line $y=x$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] For example, 0 is a fixed point of the function *f*(*x*) = 2*x*, but iteration of this function for any value other than zero rapidly diverges.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] We say that the fixed point of $f(x)=2x$ is repelling.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] An attracting fixed point is said to be a *stable fixed point* if it is also Lyapunov stable.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] A fixed point is said to be a *neutrally stable fixed point* if it is Lyapunov stable but not attracting.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] The center of a linear homogeneous differential equation of the second order is an example of a neutrally stable fixed point.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Multiple attracting points can be collected in an *attracting fixed set*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] The Banach fixed-point theorem gives a sufficient condition for the existence of attracting fixed points.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] A contraction mapping function f defined on a complete metric space has precisely one fixed point, and the fixed-point iteration is attracted towards that fixed point for any initial guess $x_{0}$ in the domain of the function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Common special cases are that (1) f is defined on the real line with real values and is Lipschitz continuous with Lipschitz constant $L<1$ , and (2) the function *f* is continuously differentiable in an open neighbourhood of a fixed point *x*fix, and $|f'(x_{\text{fix}})|<1$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Although there are other fixed-point theorems, this one in particular is very useful because not all fixed-points are attractive.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] When constructing a fixed-point iteration, it is very important to make sure it converges to the fixed point.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] We can usually use the Banach fixed-point theorem to show that the fixed point is attractive.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Attracting fixed points are a special case of a wider mathematical concept of attractors.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Fixed-point iterations are a discrete dynamical system on one variable.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Bifurcation theory studies dynamical systems and classifies various behaviors such as attracting fixed points, periodic orbits, or strange attractors.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] In computational mathematics, an iterative method is a mathematical procedure that uses an initial value to generate a sequence of improving approximate solutions for a class of problems, in which the n-th approximation is derived from the previous ones.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Convergent fixed-point iterations are mathematically rigorous formalizations of iterative methods.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] The speed of convergence of the iteration sequence can be increased by using a convergence acceleration method such as Anderson acceleration and Aitken's delta-squared process.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] The application of Aitken's method to fixed-point iteration is known as Steffensen's method, and it can be shown that Steffensen's method yields a rate of convergence that is at least quadratic.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] The term *chaos game* refers to a method of generating the fixed point of any iterated function system (IFS).
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Starting with any point *x*0, successive iterations are formed as *x**k*+1 = *f**r*(*x**k*), where *f**r* is a member of the given IFS randomly selected for each iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Hence the chaos game is a randomized fixed-point iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] The chaos game allows plotting the general shape of a fractal such as the Sierpinski triangle by repeating the iterative process a large number of times.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] More mathematically, the iterations converge to the fixed point of the IFS.
[src:newton-raphson-method/fixed-point-iteration] Whenever *x*0 belongs to the attractor of the IFS, all iterations *x**k* stay inside the attractor and, with probability 1, form a dense set in the latter.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] In numerical analysis, **Halley's method** is a root-finding algorithm used for functions of one real variable with a continuous second derivative.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Edmond Halley was an English mathematician and astronomer who introduced the method now called by his name.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] The algorithm is second in the class of Householder's methods, after Newton's method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Like the latter, it iteratively produces a sequence of approximations to the root; their rate of convergence to the root is cubic.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Multivariate versions of this method exist.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Halley's method exactly finds the roots of a linear-over-linear Padé approximation to the function, in contrast to Newton's method or the Secant method which approximate the function linearly, or Muller's method which approximates the function quadratically.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] There is also **Halley's irrational method**, described below.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Halley's method is a numerical algorithm for solving the nonlinear equation *f* (*x*) = 0 .
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] In this case, the function f has to be a function of one real variable.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] This means that the iterates converge to the zero if the initial guess is sufficiently close, and that the convergence is cubic.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] The following alternative formulation shows the similarity between Halley's method and Newton's method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] When the second derivative, $\ f''(x_{n})\ ,$ is very close to zero, the Halley's method iteration is almost the same as the Newton's method iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Also see the motivation and proofs for the more general class of Householder's methods.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Suppose *a* is a root of *f* but not of its derivative.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] And suppose that the third derivative of *f* exists and is continuous in a neighborhood of *a* and *x**n* is in that neighborhood.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] where ξ and η are numbers lying between *a* and *x**n*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Halley's rational method applied to the real-valued function *f*(*x*) is the same as applying Newton's method $x_{n+1}=x_{n}-{\frac {g(x_{n})}{g'(x_{n})}}$ to find the zeros of the function $g(x)={\frac {f(x)}{\sqrt {|kf'(x)|}}}\,,$ where k is any non-zero constant.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Applying Newton's method to *g*(*x*) will have cubic convergence (or better), whereas Newton's method applied directly to *f*(*x*) will usually have quadratic convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] For example, using Halley's method to find a zero of *f*(*x*) = *y* − *e**x*, which is useful for efficiently and precisely estimating *x* = ln(*y*), is the same as using Newton's method to find a zero of *g*(*x*) = *ye*−*x*/2 − *e**x*/2.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Just as Newton's method can be used to compute square roots, Halley's method can be specialized for the same purpose with cubic convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] This is known as the *rational form* of Halley’s method for square roots.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] It requires only arithmetic operations—no square roots—and converges cubically to ${\sqrt {S}}$ for any positive initial guess $x_{0}>0$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Halley actually developed *two* third-order root-finding methods.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] The above, using only a division, is referred to as *Halley's rational method*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] A second, "irrational" method uses a square root as well.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] The sign for the radical is chosen so that $x_{n+1}$ is the root nearer to $x_{n}$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] This iteration was "deservedly preferred" to the rational method by Halley on the grounds that it tends to have about half of the error of the rational method, a benefit which multiplies as it is iterated.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] This formulation reduces to Halley's rational method under the approximation that ⁠ ${\sqrt {1-z}}\approx 1-z/2$ ⁠.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Muller's method could be considered as modification of this method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] So, this method can be used to find the complex roots.
[src:newton-raphson-method/halley-s-method] Halley's method has been adapted to multiple variables, where the goal is to find a root ${\vec {x}}$ of ${\vec {f}}({\vec {x}})={\vec {0}}$ for some function $f\colon \mathbb {R} ^{n}\rightarrow \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with positive integer n.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In numerical analysis, the **Newton–Raphson method**, also known simply as **Newton's method**, named after Isaac Newton and Joseph Raphson, is a root-finding algorithm which produces successively better approximations to the roots (or zeroes) of a real-valued function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The most basic version starts with a real-valued function f, its derivative f′, and an initial guess *x*0 for a root of f.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] is a better approximation of the root than *x*0.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Geometrically, (*x*1, 0) is the x-intercept of the tangent to the graph of f at (*x*0, *f*(*x*0)): that is, the improved guess, *x*1, is the unique root of the linear approximation of f at the initial guess, *x*0.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] until a sufficiently precise value is reached.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The number of correct digits roughly doubles with each step.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This algorithm is first in the class of Householder's methods, and was succeeded by Halley's method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The method can also be extended to complex functions and to systems of equations.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The purpose of Newton's method is to find a root of a function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The idea is to start with an initial guess near a root, approximate the function by its tangent line near the guess, and then take the root of the linear approximation as a next guess at the function's root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This will typically be closer to the function's root than the previous guess, and the method can be iterated.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The process can be started with any arbitrary initial guess ⁠ $x_{0}$ ⁠, though it will generally require fewer iterations to converge if the guess is close to one of the function's roots.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The method will usually converge if ⁠ $f'(x_{0})\neq 0$ ⁠.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Furthermore, for a root of multiplicity 1, the convergence is at least quadratic (see *Rate of convergence*) in some sufficiently small neighbourhood of the root: the number of correct digits of the approximation roughly doubles with each additional step.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] More details can be found in *§ Analysis* below.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Householder's methods are similar but have higher order for even faster convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, the extra computations required for each step can slow down the overall performance relative to Newton's method, particularly if ⁠ f ⁠ or its derivatives are computationally expensive to evaluate.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Jamshīd al-Kāshī used a method to solve *x**P* − *N* = 0 to find roots of *N*, a method that was algebraically equivalent to Newton's method, and in which a similar method was found in *Trigonometria Britannica*, published by Henry Briggs in 1633.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] His method first appeared in his 1427 publication *Miftāḥ al-Ḥisāb* (*The Key to Arithmetic*).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Al-Kāshī's work was founded on the earlier contributions of the polymath al-Bīrūnī (973–1048) and the mathematician Sharaf al-Dīn al-Ṭūsī (1135–1213).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The contributions of al-Kāshī remained largely unknown to the Western scientific community for centuries, until the work of François Viète (1540–1603).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In 1600, Viète rediscovered a technique similar to al-Kāshī's in the context of solving scalar polynomial equations of degree six.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, while Newton gave the basic ideas, his method differs from the modern method given above.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] He applied the method only to polynomials, starting with an initial root estimate and extracting a sequence of error corrections.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] He used each correction to rewrite the polynomial in terms of the remaining error, and then solved for a new correction by neglecting higher-degree terms.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] He did not explicitly connect the method with derivatives or present a general formula.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Newton applied this method to both numerical and algebraic problems, producing Taylor series in the latter case.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Despite this, in the later second and third editions of Newton's 1687 *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica*, he did apply his method in an iterative manner to a nonpolynomial equation, specifically Kepler's equation, which were the first published uses of Newton's method in this form by him.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Newton may have derived his method from a similar, less precise method by mathematician Viète, however, the two methods are not the same.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The essence of Viète's own method can be found in the work of the mathematician Sharaf al-Din al-Tusi.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The Japanese mathematician Seki Kōwa used a form of Newton's method in the 1680s to solve single-variable equations, though the connection with calculus was missing.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Newton's method was first published in 1685 in *A Treatise of Algebra both Historical and Practical* by John Wallis.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In 1690, Raphson published a simplified description in *Analysis aequationum universalis*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Raphson also applied the method only to polynomials, but he avoided Newton's tedious rewriting process by extracting each successive correction from the original polynomial.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This allowed him to derive a reusable iterative expression for each problem.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Finally, in 1740, Simpson described Newton's method as an iterative method for solving general nonlinear equations using calculus, essentially giving the description above.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In the same publication, Simpson also gives the generalization to systems of two equations and notes that Newton's method can be used for solving optimization problems by setting the gradient to zero.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Arthur Cayley in 1879 in *The Newton–Fourier imaginary problem* was the first to notice the difficulties in generalizing Newton's method to complex roots of polynomials with degree greater than 2 and complex initial values.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This opened the way to the study of the theory of iterations of rational functions.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, there are some difficulties with the method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Newton's method requires that the derivative can be calculated directly.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] An analytical expression for the derivative may not be easily obtainable or could be expensive to evaluate.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In these situations, it may be appropriate to approximate the derivative by using the slope of a line through two nearby points on the function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Using this approximation would result in something like the secant method whose convergence is slower than that of Newton's method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] It is important to review the proof of quadratic convergence of Newton's method before implementing it.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Specifically, one should review the assumptions made in the proof.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For situations where the method fails to converge, it is because the assumptions made in this proof are not met.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For example, in some cases, if the first derivative is not well behaved in the neighborhood of a particular root, then it is possible that Newton's method will fail to converge no matter where the initialization is set.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In some cases, Newton's method can be stabilized by using successive over-relaxation, or the speed of convergence can be increased by using the same method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In a robust implementation of Newton's method, it is common to place limits on the number of iterations, bound the solution to an interval known to contain the root, and combine the method with a more robust root finding method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If the root being sought has multiplicity greater than one, the convergence rate is merely linear (errors reduced by a constant factor at each step) unless special steps are taken.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] When there are two or more roots that are close together then it may take many iterations before the iterates get close enough to one of them for the quadratic convergence to be apparent.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This is equivalent to using successive over-relaxation.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] On the other hand, if the multiplicity m of the root is not known, it is possible to estimate m after carrying out one or two iterations, and then use that value to increase the rate of convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If the multiplicity m of the root is finite then *g*(*x*) = ⁠*f*(*x*)/*f′*(*x*)⁠ will have a root at the same location with multiplicity 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Applying Newton's method to find the root of *g*(*x*) recovers quadratic convergence in many cases although it generally involves the second derivative of *f*(*x*).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The function *f*(*x*) = *x*2 has a root at 0.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Since f is continuously differentiable at its root, the theory guarantees that Newton's method as initialized sufficiently close to the root will converge.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, since the derivative *f* ′ is zero at the root, quadratic convergence is not ensured by the theory.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] It is visible from this that Newton's method could be initialized anywhere and converge to zero, but at only a linear rate.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If initialized at 1, dozens of iterations would be required before ten digits of accuracy are achieved.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The function *f*(*x*) = *x* + *x*4/3 also has a root at 0, where it is continuously differentiable.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Although the first derivative *f* ′ is nonzero at the root, the second derivative *f* ′′ is nonexistent there, so that quadratic convergence cannot be guaranteed.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] From this, it can be seen that the rate of convergence is superlinear but subquadratic.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This can be seen in the following tables, the left of which shows Newton's method applied to the above *f*(*x*) = *x* + *x*4/3 and the right of which shows Newton's method applied to *f*(*x*) = *x* + *x*2.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The quadratic convergence in iteration shown on the right is illustrated by the orders of magnitude in the distance from the iterate to the true root (0,1,2,3,5,10,20,39,...) being approximately doubled from row to row.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] While the convergence on the left is superlinear, the order of magnitude is only multiplied by about 4/3 from row to row (0,1,2,4,5,7,10,13,...).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The rate of convergence is distinguished from the number of iterations required to reach a given accuracy.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For example, the function *f*(*x*) = *x*20 − 1 has a root at 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Since *f* ′(1) ≠ 0 and f is smooth, it is known that any Newton iteration convergent to 1 will converge quadratically.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, if initialized at 0.5, the first few iterates of Newton's method are approximately 26214, 24904, 23658, 22476, decreasing slowly, with only the 200th iterate being 1.0371.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This highlights that quadratic convergence of a Newton iteration does not mean that only few iterates are required; this only applies once the sequence of iterates is sufficiently close to the root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] From this, it can be seen that there are three possible phenomena for a Newton iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If initialized strictly between ±1, the Newton iteration will converge (super-)quadratically to 0; if initialized exactly at 1 or −1, the Newton iteration will oscillate endlessly between ±1; if initialized anywhere else, the Newton iteration will diverge.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This same trichotomy occurs for *f*(*x*) = arctan *x*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In cases where the function in question has multiple roots, it can be difficult to control, via choice of initialization, which root (if any) is identified by Newton's method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If initialized at −1.488, the Newton iteration converges to 0; if initialized at −1.487, it diverges to ∞; if initialized at −1.486, it converges to −1; if initialized at −1.485, it diverges to −∞; if initialized at −1.4843, it converges to 3; if initialized at −1.484, it converges to 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This kind of subtle dependence on initialization is not uncommon; it is frequently studied in the complex plane in the form of the Newton fractal.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Consider the problem of finding a root of *f*(*x*) = *x*1/3.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Unless Newton's method is initialized at the exact root 0, it is seen that the sequence of iterates will fail to converge.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This failure of convergence is not contradicted by the analytic theory, since in this case f is not differentiable at its root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In the above example, failure of convergence is reflected by the failure of *f*(*x**n*) to get closer to zero as n increases, as well as by the fact that successive iterates are growing further and further apart.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In this example, where again f is not differentiable at the root, any Newton iteration not starting exactly at the root will diverge, but with both *x**n* + 1 − *x**n* and *f*(*x**n*) converging to zero.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Although the convergence of *x**n* + 1 − *x**n* in this case is not very rapid, it can be proved from the iteration formula.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This example highlights the possibility that a stopping criterion for Newton's method based only on the smallness of *x**n* + 1 − *x**n* and *f*(*x**n*) might falsely identify a root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] It is easy to find situations for which Newton's method oscillates endlessly between two distinct values.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For example, for Newton's method as applied to a function f to oscillate between 0 and 1, it is only necessary that the tangent line to f at 0 intersects the x-axis at 1 and that the tangent line to f at 1 intersects the x-axis at 0.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For this function, it is even the case that Newton's iteration as initialized sufficiently close to 0 or 1 will *asymptotically* oscillate between these values.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This behavior is present despite the presence of a root of f approximately equal to −1.76929.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In some cases, it is not even possible to perform the Newton iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] So Newton's method cannot be initialized at 0, since this would make *x*1 undefined.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Geometrically, this is because the tangent line to f at 0 is horizontal (i.e.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Even if the initialization is selected so that the Newton iteration can begin, the same phenomenon can block the iteration from being indefinitely continued.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If f has an incomplete domain, it is possible for Newton's method to send the iterates outside of the domain, so that it is impossible to continue the iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For example, the natural logarithm function *f*(*x*) = ln *x* has a root at 1, and is defined only for positive x.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] So if the iteration is initialized at e, the next iterate is 0; if the iteration is initialized at a value larger than e, then the next iterate is negative.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In either case, the method cannot be continued.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Suppose that the function f has a zero at α, i.e., *f*(*α*) = 0, and f is differentiable in a neighborhood of α.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If f is continuously differentiable and its derivative is nonzero at α, then there exists a neighborhood of α such that for all starting values *x*0 in that neighborhood, the sequence (*x**n*) will converge to α.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If f is continuously differentiable, its derivative is nonzero at α, *and* it has a second derivative at α, then the convergence is quadratic or faster.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If the second derivative is not 0 at α then the convergence is merely quadratic.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If the derivative is 0 at α, then the convergence is usually only linear.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Specifically, if f is twice continuously differentiable, *f′*(*α*) = 0 and *f″*(*α*) ≠ 0, then there exists a neighborhood of α such that, for all starting values *x*0 in that neighborhood, the sequence of iterates converges linearly, with rate ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Alternatively, if *f′*(*α*) = 0 and *f′*(*x*) ≠ 0 for *x* ≠ *α*, x in a neighborhood U of α, α being a zero of multiplicity r, and if *f* ∈ *C**r*(*U*), then there exists a neighborhood of α such that, for all starting values *x*0 in that neighborhood, the sequence of iterates converges linearly.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, even linear convergence is not guaranteed in pathological situations.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In practice, these results are local, and the neighborhood of convergence is not known in advance.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] But there are also some results on global convergence: for instance, given a right neighborhood *U*+ of α, if f is twice differentiable in *U*+ and if *f′* ≠ 0, *f* · *f″* > 0 in *U*+, then, for each *x*0 in *U*+ the sequence *x**k* is monotonically decreasing to α.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] According to Taylor's theorem, any function *f*(*x*) which has a continuous second derivative can be represented by an expansion about a point that is close to a root of *f*(*x*).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] where *ξ**n* is in between *x**n* and α.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Suppose that *f*(*x*) is a concave function on an interval, which is strictly increasing.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If it is negative at the left endpoint and positive at the right endpoint, the intermediate value theorem guarantees that there is a zero ζ of f somewhere in the interval.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] From geometrical principles, it can be seen that the Newton iteration *x**i* starting at the left endpoint is monotonically increasing and convergent, necessarily to ζ.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This sequence is monotonically decreasing and convergent.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] By passing to the limit in this definition, it can be seen that the limit of *y**i* must also be the zero ζ.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] So, in the case of a concave increasing function with a zero, initialization is largely irrelevant.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Newton iteration starting anywhere left of the zero will converge, as will Fourier's modified Newton iteration starting anywhere right of the zero.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The accuracy at any step of the iteration can be determined directly from the difference between the location of the iteration from the left and the location of the iteration from the right.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] showing that this difference in locations converges quadratically to zero.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] All of the above can be extended to systems of equations in multiple variables, although in that context the relevant concepts of monotonicity and concavity are more subtle to formulate.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In the case of single equations in a single variable, the above monotonic convergence of Newton's method can also be generalized to replace concavity by positivity or negativity conditions on an arbitrary higher-order derivative of f.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, in this generalization, Newton's iteration is modified so as to be based on Taylor polynomials rather than the tangent line.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In the case of concavity, this modification coincides with the standard Newton method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Newton's method is one of many known methods of computing square roots.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Given a positive number a, the problem of finding a number x such that *x*2 = *a* is equivalent to finding a root of the function *f*(*x*) = *x*2 − *a*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This happens to coincide with the "Babylonian" method of finding square roots, which consists of replacing an approximate root *x**n* by the arithmetic mean of *x**n* and *a*⁄*x**n*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] By performing this iteration, it is possible to evaluate a square root to any desired accuracy by only using the basic arithmetic operations.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The following three tables show examples of the result of this computation for finding the square root of 612, with the iteration initialized at the values of 1, 10, and −20.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] It is seen that with only a few iterations one can obtain a solution accurate to many decimal places.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The first table shows that this is true even if the Newton iteration were initialized by the very inaccurate guess of 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] When computing any nonzero square root, the first derivative of f must be nonzero at the root, and that f is a smooth function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] So, even before any computation, it is known that any convergent Newton iteration has a quadratic rate of convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This is reflected in the above tables by the fact that once a Newton iterate gets close to the root, the number of correct digits approximately doubles with each iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Consider the problem of finding the positive number x with cos (*x*) = *x*3.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] We can rephrase that as finding the zero of *f*(*x*) = cos(*x*) − *x*3.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Since cos(*x*) ≤ 1 for all x and *x*3 > 1 for *x* > 1, we know that our solution lies between 0 and 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] A starting value of 0 will lead to an undefined result which illustrates the importance of using a starting point close to the solution.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The correct digits are underlined in the above example.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In particular, *x*6 is correct to 12 decimal places.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] We see that the number of correct digits after the decimal point increases from 2 (for *x*3) to 5 and 10, illustrating the quadratic convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The k-dimensional variant of Newton's method can be used to solve systems of greater than k (nonlinear) equations as well if the algorithm uses the generalized inverse of the non-square Jacobian matrix *J*+ = (*J*T*J*)−1*J*T instead of the inverse of J.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If the nonlinear system has no solution, the method attempts to find a solution in the non-linear least squares sense.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] See Gauss–Newton algorithm for more information.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] A milk carton with a capacity of 2 pints is to be constructed from a sheet of waxed carboard with a 5mm overlap.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The requirement is that the minimum surface area is used for the carton.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Suppose the width, breadth and height of the carton are denoted by w , b and h respectively, in millimetres.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Since all eigenvalues are positive, $\mathbf {J} (\mathbf {x} _{8})$ is positive definite, and therefore $\mathbf {x} _{8}$ is a minimum.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] When dealing with complex functions, Newton's method can be directly applied to find their zeroes.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Each zero has a basin of attraction in the complex plane, the set of all starting values that cause the method to converge to that particular zero.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] These sets can be mapped as in the image shown.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For many complex functions, the boundaries of the basins of attraction are fractals.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In some cases there are regions in the complex plane which are not in any of these basins of attraction, meaning the iterates do not converge.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For example, if one uses a real initial condition to seek a root of *x*2 + 1, all subsequent iterates will be real numbers and so the iterations cannot converge to either root, since both roots are non-real.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In this case almost all real initial conditions lead to chaotic behavior, while some initial conditions iterate either to infinity or to repeating cycles of any finite length.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Curt McMullen has shown that for any possible purely iterative algorithm similar to Newton's method, the algorithm will diverge on some open regions of the complex plane when applied to some polynomial of degree 4 or higher.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, McMullen gave a generally convergent algorithm for polynomials of degree 3.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Also, for any polynomial, Hubbard, Schleicher, and Sutherland gave a method for selecting a set of initial points such that Newton's method will certainly converge at one of them at least.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Another generalization is Newton's method to find a root of a functional F defined in a Banach space.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] where *F′*(*X**n*) is the Fréchet derivative computed at *X**n*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] One needs the Fréchet derivative to be boundedly invertible at each *X**n* in order for the method to be applicable.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] A condition for existence of and convergence to a root is given by the Newton–Kantorovich theorem.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In the 1950s, John Nash developed a version of the Newton's method to apply to the problem of constructing isometric embeddings of general Riemannian manifolds in Euclidean space.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The *loss of derivatives* problem, present in this context, made the standard Newton iteration inapplicable, since it could not be continued indefinitely (much less converge).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Nash's solution involved the introduction of smoothing operators into the iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] He was able to prove the convergence of his smoothed Newton method, for the purpose of proving an implicit function theorem for isometric embeddings.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In the 1960s, Jürgen Moser showed that Nash's methods were flexible enough to apply to problems beyond isometric embedding, particularly in celestial mechanics.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Since then, a number of mathematicians, including Mikhael Gromov and Richard Hamilton, have found generalized abstract versions of the Nash–Moser theory.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In Hamilton's formulation, the Nash–Moser theorem forms a generalization of the Banach space Newton method which takes place in certain Fréchet spaces.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] When the Jacobian is unavailable or too expensive to compute at every iteration, a quasi-Newton method can be used.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Since higher-order Taylor expansions offer more accurate local approximations of a function f, it is reasonable to ask why Newton’s method relies only on a second-order Taylor approximation.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In the 19th century, Russian mathematician Pafnuty Chebyshev explored this idea by developing a variant of Newton’s method that used cubic approximations.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] In p-adic analysis, the standard method to show a polynomial equation in one variable has a p-adic root is Hensel's lemma, which uses the recursion from Newton's method on the p-adic numbers.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Newton's method can be generalized with the q-analog of the usual derivative.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] A nonlinear equation has multiple solutions in general.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] But if the initial value is not appropriate, Newton's method may not converge to the desired solution or may converge to the same solution found earlier.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This method is applied to obtain zeros of the Bessel function of the second kind.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Hirano's modified Newton method is a modification conserving the convergence of Newton method and avoiding unstableness.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] It is developed to solve complex polynomials.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Combining Newton's method with interval arithmetic is very useful in some contexts.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This provides a stopping criterion that is more reliable than the usual ones (which are a small value of the function or a small variation of the variable between consecutive iterations).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] We also assume that 0 ∉ *F′*(*X*), so in particular f has at most one root in X.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Note that the hypothesis on F′ implies that *N*(*Y*) is well defined and is an interval (see interval arithmetic for further details on interval operations).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The mean value theorem ensures that if there is a root of f in *X**k*, then it is also in *X**k* + 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Moreover, the hypothesis on F′ ensures that *X**k* + 1 is at most half the size of *X**k* when m is the midpoint of Y, so this sequence converges towards [*x**, *x**], where x* is the root of f in X.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] If *F′*(*X*) strictly contains 0, the use of extended interval division produces a union of two intervals for *N*(*X*); multiple roots are therefore automatically separated and bounded.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Newton's method can be used to find a minimum or maximum of a function *f*(*x*).
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The derivative is zero at a minimum or maximum, so local minima and maxima can be found by applying Newton's method to the derivative.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] An important application is Newton–Raphson division, which can be used to quickly find the reciprocal of a number a, using only multiplication and subtraction, that is to say the number x such that ⁠1/*x*⁠ = *a*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] We can rephrase that as finding the zero of *f*(*x*) = ⁠1/*x*⁠ − *a*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Therefore, Newton's iteration needs only two multiplications and one subtraction.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] This method is also very efficient to compute the multiplicative inverse of a power series.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Many transcendental equations can be solved up to an arbitrary precision by using Newton's method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For example, finding the cumulative probability density function, such as a Normal distribution to fit a known probability generally involves integral functions with no known means to solve in closed form.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] However, computing the derivatives needed to solve them numerically with Newton's method is generally known, making numerical solutions possible.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] For an example, see the numerical solution to the inverse Normal cumulative distribution.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] A numerical verification for solutions of nonlinear equations has been established by using Newton's method multiple times and forming a set of solution candidates.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The following is an example of a possible implementation of Newton's method in the Python (version 3.x) programming language for finding a root of a function `f` which has derivative `f_prime`.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] The initial guess will be *x*0 = 1 and the function will be *f*(*x*) = *x*2 − 2 so that *f′*(*x*) = 2*x*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] Each new iteration of Newton's method will be denoted by `x1`.
[src:newton-raphson-method/newton-s-method] We will check during the computation whether the denominator (`y_prime`) becomes too small (smaller than `epsilon`), which would be the case if *f′*(*x**n*) ≈ 0, since otherwise a large amount of error could be introduced.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] In mathematical analysis, particularly numerical analysis, the **rate of convergence** and **order of convergence** of a sequence that converges to a limit are any of several characterizations of how quickly that sequence approaches its limit.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Asymptotic rates and orders of convergence are the focus of this article.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] In formal mathematics, rates of convergence and orders of convergence are often described comparatively using asymptotic notation commonly called "big O notation," which can be used to encompass both of the prior conventions; this is an application of asymptotic analysis.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Where methodological precision is required, these rates and orders of convergence are known specifically as the rates and orders of Q-convergence, short for quotient-convergence, since the limit in question is a quotient of error terms.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Similar concepts are used for sequences of discretizations.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] For instance, ideally the solution of a differential equation discretized via a regular grid will converge to the solution of the continuous equation as the grid spacing goes to zero, and if so the asymptotic rate and order of that convergence are important properties of the gridding method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] where the absolute value symbols stand for a metric for the space of solutions such as the uniform norm.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] and the two are said to asymptotically converge with the same order of convergence if the limit is any positive finite value.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] The two are said to be asymptotically equivalent if the limit is equal to one.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] These comparative definitions of rate and order of asymptotic convergence are fundamental in asymptotic analysis and find wide application in mathematical analysis as a whole, including numerical analysis, real analysis, complex analysis, and functional analysis.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Suppose that the sequence $(x_{k})$ of iterates of an iterative method converges to the limit number L as $k\rightarrow \infty$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Other more technical rate definitions are needed if the sequence converges but ${\textstyle \lim _{k\to \infty }{\frac {|x_{k+1}-L|}{|x_{k}-L|}}=1}$ or the limit does not exist.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] This definition is technically called Q-convergence, short for quotient-convergence, and the rates and orders are called rates and orders of Q-convergence when that technical specificity is needed. § R-convergence, below, is an appropriate alternative when this limit does not exist.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Sequences with larger orders q converge more quickly than those with smaller order, and those with smaller rates $\mu$ converge more quickly than those with larger rates for a given order.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] This "smaller rates converge more quickly" behavior among sequences of the same order is standard but it can be counterintuitive.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Therefore it is also common to define $-\log _{10}\mu$ as the rate; this is the "number of extra decimals of precision per iterate" for sequences that converge with order 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Integer powers of q are common and are given common names.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Convergence with order $q=1$ and $\mu \in (0,1)$ is called *linear convergence* and the sequence is said to *converge linearly to L*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Convergence with $q=2$ and any $\mu$ is called *quadratic convergence* and the sequence is said to *converge quadratically*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Convergence with $q=3$ and any $\mu$ is called *cubic convergence*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] However, it is not necessary that q be an integer.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] For example, the secant method, when converging to a regular, simple root, has an order of the golden ratio φ ≈ 1.618.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] The common names for integer orders of convergence connect to asymptotic big O notation, where the convergence of the quotient implies ${\textstyle |x_{k+1}-L|=O(|x_{k}-L|^{q}).}$ These are linear, quadratic, and cubic polynomial expressions when q is 1, 2, and 3, respectively.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] In general, when $q>1$ for a sequence or for any sequence that satisfies ${\textstyle \lim _{k\to \infty }{\frac {|x_{k+1}-L|}{|x_{k}-L|}}=0,}$ those sequences are said to *converge superlinearly* (i.e., faster than linearly).
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] A sequence is said to *converge sublinearly* (i.e., slower than linearly) if it converges and ${\textstyle \lim _{k\to \infty }{\frac {|x_{k+1}-L|}{|x_{k}-L|}}=1.}$ Importantly, it is incorrect to say that these sublinear-order sequences converge linearly with an asymptotic rate of convergence of 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] The definitions of Q-convergence rates have the shortcoming that they do not naturally capture the convergence behavior of sequences that do converge, but do not converge with an asymptotically constant rate with every step, so that the Q-convergence limit does not exist.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] The defining Q-linear convergence limits do not exist for this sequence because one subsequence of error quotients starting from odd steps converges to 1 and another subsequence of quotients starting from even steps converges to 1/4.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] When two subsequences of a sequence converge to different limits, the sequence does not itself converge to a limit.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] In cases like these, a closely related but more technical definition of rate of convergence called R-convergence is more appropriate.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Any error bounding sequence $(\varepsilon _{k})$ provides a lower bound on the rate and order of R-convergence and the greatest lower bound gives the exact rate and order of R-convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Thus $(a_{k})$ converges Q-linearly with a convergence rate of $\mu =1/2$ ; see the first plot of the figure below.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] In fact, it is quadratically convergent with a quadratic convergence rate of 1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] It is shown in the third plot of the figure below.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Recurrent sequences ${\textstyle x_{k+1}:=f(x_{k})}$ , called fixed point iterations, define discrete time autonomous dynamical systems and have important general applications in mathematics through various fixed-point theorems about their convergence behavior.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] When *f* is continuously differentiable, given a fixed point *p*, ${\textstyle f(p)=p,}$ such that ${\textstyle |f'(p)|<1}$ , the fixed point is an attractive fixed point and the recurrent sequence will converge at least linearly to *p* for any starting value $x_{0}$ sufficiently close to *p*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] If $|f'(p)|=0$ and ${\textstyle |f''(p)|<1}$ , then the recurrent sequence will converge at least quadratically, and so on.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] If $|f'(p)|>1$ , then the fixed point is a repulsive fixed point and sequences cannot converge to *p* from its immediate neighborhoods, though they may still jump to *p* directly from outside of its local neighborhoods.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] For numerical approximation of an exact value through a numerical method of order q see.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Many methods exist to accelerate the convergence of a given sequence, i.e., to transform one sequence into a second sequence that converges more quickly to the same limit.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Such techniques are in general known as "series acceleration" methods.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] These may reduce the computational costs of approximating the limits of the original sequences.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] One example of series acceleration by sequence transformation is Aitken's delta-squared process.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] On the other hand, if the convergence is already of order ≥ 2, Aitken's method will bring no improvement.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] for some positive constants $\mu$ and q and using $|x|$ to stand for an appropriate distance metric on the space of solutions, most often either the uniform norm, the absolute difference, or the Euclidean distance.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] When all the discretizations are generated using a single common method, it is common to discuss the asymptotic rate and order of convergence for the method itself rather than any particular discrete sequences of discretized solutions.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] again for some positive constants $\mu$ and q and an appropriate metric $|x|.$ This implies that the error of a discretization asymptotically scales like the discretization's scale parameter to the q power, or ${\textstyle \left|y_{h}-S\right|=O(h^{q})}$ using asymptotic big O notation.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] for any sequence of grids with successively smaller grid spacings $h_{k}$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] These comparative definitions of rate and order of asymptotic convergence are fundamental in asymptotic analysis.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] For the first two of these there are associated expressions in asymptotic O notation: the first is that $a_{k}-L=o(b_{k}-L)$ in small o notation and the second is that $a_{k}-L=\Theta (b_{k}-L)$ in Knuth notation.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Non-asymptotic rates of convergence do not have the common, standard definitions that asymptotic rates of convergence have.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] Among formal techniques, Lyapunov theory is one of the most powerful and widely applied frameworks for characterizing and analyzing non-asymptotic convergence behavior.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] For iterative methods, one common practical approach is to discuss these rates in terms of the number of iterates or the computer time required to reach close neighborhoods of a limit from starting points far from the limit.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] The non-asymptotic rate is then an inverse of that number of iterates or computer time.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] In practical applications, an iterative method that required fewer steps or less computer time than another to reach target accuracy will be said to have converged faster than the other, even if its asymptotic convergence is slower.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] These rates will generally be different for different starting points and different error thresholds for defining the neighborhoods.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] For discretized approximation methods, similar approaches can be used with a discretization scale parameter such as an inverse of a number of grid or mesh points or a Fourier series cutoff frequency playing the role of inverse iterate number, though it is not especially common.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] For any problem, there is a greatest discretization scale parameter compatible with a desired accuracy of approximation, and it may not be as small as required for the asymptotic rate and order of convergence to provide accurate estimates of the error.
[src:newton-raphson-method/rate-of-convergence] In practical applications, when one discretization method gives a desired accuracy with a larger discretization scale parameter than another it will often be said to converge faster than the other, even if its eventual asymptotic convergence is slower.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] In numerical analysis, a **root-finding algorithm** is an algorithm for finding zeros, also called "roots", of continuous functions.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] A zero of a function *f* is a number *x* such that *f*(*x*) = 0.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] As, generally, the zeros of a function cannot be computed exactly nor expressed in closed form, root-finding algorithms provide approximations to zeros.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] For functions from the real numbers to real numbers or from the complex numbers to the complex numbers, these are expressed either as floating-point numbers without error bounds or as floating-point values together with error bounds.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The latter, approximations with error bounds, are equivalent to small isolating intervals for real roots or disks for complex roots.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Thus root-finding algorithms can be used to solve any equation of continuous functions.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] However, most root-finding algorithms do not guarantee that they will find all roots of a function, and if such an algorithm does not find any root, that does not necessarily mean that no root exists.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Most numerical root-finding methods are iterative methods, producing a sequence of numbers that ideally converges towards a root as a limit.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] They require one or more *initial guesses* of the root as starting values, then each iteration of the algorithm produces a successively more accurate approximation to the root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Since the iteration must be stopped at some point, these methods produce an approximation to the root, not an exact solution.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Many methods compute subsequent values by evaluating an auxiliary function on the preceding values.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The limit is thus a fixed point of the auxiliary function, which is chosen for having the roots of the original equation as fixed points and for converging rapidly to these fixed points.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The behavior of general root-finding algorithms is studied in numerical analysis.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] However, for polynomials specifically, the study of root-finding algorithms belongs to computer algebra, since algebraic properties of polynomials are fundamental for the most efficient algorithms.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The efficiency and applicability of an algorithm may depend sensitively on the characteristics of the given functions.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] For example, many algorithms use the derivative of the input function, while others work on every continuous function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] In general, numerical algorithms are not guaranteed to find all the roots of a function, so failing to find a root does not prove that there is no root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Bracketing methods determine successively smaller intervals (brackets) that contain a root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] When the interval is small enough, then a root is considered found.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] These generally use the intermediate value theorem, which asserts that if a continuous function has values of opposite signs at the end points of an interval, then the function has at least one root in the interval.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Therefore, they require starting with an interval such that the function takes opposite signs at the end points of the interval.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] However, in the case of polynomials there are other methods such as Descartes' rule of signs, Budan's theorem and Sturm's theorem for bounding or determining the number of roots in an interval.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] They lead to efficient algorithms for real-root isolation of polynomials, which find all real roots with a guaranteed accuracy.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The simplest root-finding algorithm is the bisection method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Let *f* be a continuous function for which one knows an interval [*a*, *b*] such that *f*(*a*) and *f*(*b*) have opposite signs (a bracket).
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Let *c* = (*a* + *b*)/2 be the middle of the interval (the midpoint or the point that bisects the interval).
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Then either *f*(*a*) and *f*(*c*), or *f*(*c*) and *f*(*b*) have opposite signs, and one has divided by two the size of the interval.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Although the bisection method is robust, it gains one and only one bit of accuracy with each iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Therefore, the number of function evaluations required for finding an *ε*-approximate root is $\log _{2}{\frac {b-a}{\varepsilon }}$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Other methods, under appropriate conditions, can gain accuracy faster.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] False position is similar to the secant method, except that, instead of retaining the last two points, it makes sure to keep one point on either side of the root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The false position method can be faster than the bisection method and will never diverge like the secant method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] However, it may fail to converge in some naive implementations due to roundoff errors that may lead to a wrong sign for *f*(*c*).
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Typically, this may occur if the derivative of f is large in the neighborhood of the root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Many root-finding processes work by interpolation.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] This consists in using the last computed approximate values of the root for approximating the function by a polynomial of low degree, which takes the same values at these approximate roots.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Then the root of the polynomial is computed and used as a new approximate value of the root of the function, and the process is iterated.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Interpolating two values yields a line: a polynomial of degree one.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] *Regula falsi* is also an interpolation method that interpolates two points at a time but it differs from the secant method by using two points that are not necessarily the last two computed points.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Three values define a parabolic curve: a quadratic function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Although all root-finding algorithms proceed by iteration, an iterative root-finding method generally uses a specific type of iteration, consisting of defining an auxiliary function, which is applied to the last computed approximations of a root for getting a new approximation.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The iteration stops when a fixed point of the auxiliary function is reached to the desired precision, i.e., when a new computed value is sufficiently close to the preceding ones.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Newton's method assumes the function *f* to have a continuous derivative.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Newton's method may not converge if started too far away from a root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] However, when it does converge, it is faster than the bisection method; its order of convergence is usually quadratic whereas the bisection method's is linear.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Newton's method is also important because it readily generalizes to higher-dimensional problems.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Householder's methods are a class of Newton-like methods with higher orders of convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The first one after Newton's method is Halley's method with cubic order of convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Replacing the derivative in Newton's method with a finite difference, we get the secant method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] This method does not require the computation (nor the existence) of a derivative, but the price is slower convergence (the order of convergence is the golden ratio, approximately 1.62).
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] A generalization of the secant method in higher dimensions is Broyden's method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] We can use the fixed-point iteration to find the root of a function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Given a function $f(x)$ which we have set to zero to find the root ( $f(x)=0$ ), we rewrite the equation in terms of x so that $f(x)=0$ becomes $x=g(x)$ (note, there are often many $g(x)$ functions for each $f(x)=0$ function).
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Next, we relabel each side of the equation as $x_{n+1}=g(x_{n})$ so that we can perform the iteration.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Next, we pick a value for $x_{1}$ and perform the iteration until it converges towards a root of the function.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] If the iteration converges, it will converge to a root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The iteration will only converge if $|g'(root)|<1$ .
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] As an example of converting $f(x)=0$ to $x=g(x)$ , if given the function $f(x)=x^{2}+x-1$ , we will rewrite it as one of the following equations.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The appearance of complex values in interpolation methods can be avoided by interpolating the inverse of *f*, resulting in the inverse quadratic interpolation method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Again, convergence is asymptotically faster than the secant method, but inverse quadratic interpolation often behaves poorly when the iterates are not close to the root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Brent's method is a combination of the bisection method, the secant method and inverse quadratic interpolation.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] At every iteration, Brent's method decides which method out of these three is likely to do best, and proceeds by doing a step according to that method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] This gives a robust and fast method, which therefore enjoys considerable popularity.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Ridders' method is a hybrid method that uses the value of function at the midpoint of the interval to perform an exponential interpolation to the root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] This gives a fast convergence with a guaranteed convergence of at most twice the number of iterations as the bisection method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Finding the roots of polynomials is a long-standing problem that has been extensively studied throughout the history and substantially influenced the development of mathematics.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] where $a_{i}$ are either real or complex numbers.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Efforts to understand and solve polynomial equations led to the development of important mathematical concepts, including irrational and complex numbers, as well as foundational structures in modern algebra such as fields, rings, and groups.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Despite being historically important, finding the roots of higher degree polynomials no longer play a central role in mathematics and computational mathematics, with one major exception in computer algebra.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The bisection method has been generalized to higher dimensions; these methods are called **generalized bisection methods**.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] At each iteration, the domain is partitioned into two parts, and the algorithm decides - based on a small number of function evaluations - which of these two parts must contain a root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] In one dimension, the criterion for decision is that the function has opposite signs.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The main challenge in extending the method to multiple dimensions is to find a criterion that can be computed easily and guarantees the existence of a root.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The Poincaré–Miranda theorem gives a criterion for the existence of a root in a rectangle, but it is hard to verify because it requires evaluating the function on the entire boundary of the rectangle.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Another criterion is given by a theorem of Kronecker.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] It says that, if the topological degree of a function *f* on a rectangle is non-zero, then the rectangle must contain at least one root of *f*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] This criterion is the basis for several root-finding methods, such as those of Stenger and Kearfott.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] However, computing the topological degree can be time-consuming.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] A third criterion is based on a *characteristic polyhedron*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] This criterion is used by a method called Characteristic Bisection.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] It does not require computing the topological degree; it only requires computing the signs of function values.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] The number of required evaluations is at least $\log _{2}(D/\epsilon )$ , where *D* is the length of the longest edge of the characteristic polyhedron.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Note that Vrahatis and Iordanidis prove a lower bound on the number of evaluations, and not an upper bound.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] A fourth method uses an intermediate value theorem on simplices.
[src:newton-raphson-method/root-finding-algorithm] Again, no upper bound on the number of queries is given.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] In numerical analysis, the **secant method** is a root-finding algorithm that uses a succession of roots of secant lines to better approximate a root of a function *f*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] The secant method can be thought of as a finite-difference approximation of Newton's method, so it is considered a quasi-Newton method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] Historically, it is as an evolution of the method of false position, which predates Newton's method by over 3000 years.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] The secant method is an iterative numerical method for finding a zero of a function f.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] This is a nonlinear second-order recurrence that is well-defined given f and the two initial values *x*0 and *x*1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] Ideally, the initial values should be chosen close to the desired zero.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] Starting with initial values *x*0 and *x*1, we construct a line through the points (*x*0, *f*(*x*0)) and (*x*1, *f*(*x*1)), as shown in the picture above.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] We then use this new value of x as *x*2 and repeat the process, using *x*1 and *x*2 instead of *x*0 and *x*1.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] The iterates $x_{n}$ of the secant method converge to a root of f if the initial values $x_{0}$ and $x_{1}$ are sufficiently close to the root and f is well-behaved.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] When f is twice continuously differentiable and the root in question is a simple root, i.e., it has multiplicity 1, the order of convergence is the golden ratio $\varphi =(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2\approx 1.618.$ This convergence is superlinear but subquadratic.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] If the initial values are not close enough to the root or f is not well-behaved, then there is no guarantee that the secant method converges at all.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] There is no general definition of "close enough", but the criterion for convergence has to do with how "wiggly" the function is on the interval between the initial values.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] For example, if f is differentiable on that interval and there is a point where $f'=0$ on the interval, then the algorithm may not converge.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] The secant method does not require or guarantee that the root remains bracketed by sequential iterates, like the bisection method does, and hence it does not always converge.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] The false position method (or *regula falsi*) uses the same formula as the secant method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] However, it does not apply the formula on $x_{n-1}$ and $x_{n-2}$ , like the secant method, but on $x_{n-1}$ and on the last iterate $x_{k}$ such that $f(x_{k})$ and $f(x_{n-1})$ have a different sign.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] This means that the false position method always converges; however, only with a linear order of convergence.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] Bracketing with a super-linear order of convergence as the secant method can be attained with improvements to the false position method (see Regula falsi § Improvements in *regula falsi*) such as the ITP method or the Illinois method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] The secant method can be interpreted as a method in which the derivative is replaced by an approximation and is thus a quasi-Newton method.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] If we compare Newton's method with the secant method, we see that Newton's method converges faster (order 2 against order the golden ratio *φ* ≈ 1.6).
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] However, Newton's method requires the evaluation of both f and its derivative $f'$ at every step, while the secant method only requires the evaluation of f .
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] Therefore, the secant method may sometimes be faster in practice.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] In higher dimensions, the full set of partial derivatives required for Newton's method, that is, the Jacobian matrix, may become much more expensive to calculate than the function itself.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] If, however, we consider parallel processing for the evaluation of the derivative or derivatives, Newton's method can be faster in clock time though still costing more computational operations overall.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] Broyden's method is a generalization of the secant method to more than one dimension.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] The following graph shows the function *f* in red and the last secant line in bold blue.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] In the graph, the *x* intercept of the secant line seems to be a good approximation of the root of *f*.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] Below, the secant method is implemented in the Python programming language.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] It is very important to have a good stopping criterion above, otherwise, due to limited numerical precision of floating point numbers, the algorithm can return inaccurate results if running for too many iterations.
[src:newton-raphson-method/secant-method] For example, the loop above can stop when one of these is reached first: abs(x0 - x1) < tol, or abs(x0/x1-1) < tol, or abs(f(x1)) < tol.
